There are multiple ways to set a node's position:

```typescript
// Method 1: setPosition with x, y
node.setPosition(100, 200);

// Method 2: setPosition with cc.Point
node.setPosition(cc.p(100, 200));

// Method 3: Direct property access (faster)
node.x = 100;
node.y = 200;

// Read position
const pos = node.getPosition(); // returns cc.Point
const x = node.getPositionX();
const y = node.getPositionY();
```

Direct property access (`node.x`, `node.y`) is faster than getter/setter methods in the JS binding.

The anchor point defines the origin for positioning, rotation, and scale. Values range from 0 to 1:

```typescript
// Center anchor (default for Sprite)
node.setAnchorPoint(cc.p(0.5, 0.5));

// Bottom-left anchor (default for Layer)
node.setAnchorPoint(cc.p(0, 0));

// Top-right
node.setAnchorPoint(0.5, 1.0);

// Read anchor
const anchor = node.getAnchorPoint();         // normalized (0-1)
const anchorPx = node.getAnchorPointInPoints(); // in pixels

// Direct properties
node.anchorX = 0.5;
node.anchorY = 0.5;
```

For Layers, you may want `node.ignoreAnchorPointForPosition(true)` which forces positioning from the bottom-left regardless of anchor point.

Use `setContentSize` to define the node's dimensions:

```typescript
// With cc.Size
node.setContentSize(cc.size(200, 100));

// With width and height
node.setContentSize(200, 100);

// Read size
const size = node.getContentSize(); // cc.Size
const w = size.width;
const h = size.height;

// Direct properties
node.width = 200;
node.height = 100;
```

Content size affects bounding box calculations, anchor point pixel positions, and child positioning.

Use `addChild` and the various remove methods:

```typescript
const parent = new cc.Node();
const child = new cc.Sprite('img.png');

// Add with optional zOrder and tag
parent.addChild(child);
parent.addChild(child, 5);           // zOrder = 5
parent.addChild(child, 5, 'hero');   // zOrder = 5, name = 'hero'
parent.addChild(child, 5, 100);      // zOrder = 5, tag = 100

// Remove
parent.removeChild(child, true);       // cleanup = true (stops actions/timers)
parent.removeChildByTag(100);
parent.removeChildByName('hero');
parent.removeAllChildren();

// Remove self from parent
child.removeFromParent(true);

// Find children
const found = parent.getChildByTag(100);
const hero = parent.getChildByName('hero');
const all = parent.getChildren();       // cc.Node[]
const count = parent.getChildrenCount();
```

Use visibility and opacity properties:

```typescript
// Visibility (binary on/off)
node.setVisible(false);
node.setVisible(true);
const vis = node.isVisible();
node.visible = false; // direct property

// Opacity (0 = transparent, 255 = opaque)
node.setOpacity(128);    // 50% transparent
const op = node.getOpacity();
node.opacity = 200;      // direct property

// Cascade opacity to children
node.setCascadeOpacityEnabled(true);
// Now children inherit this node's opacity

// Displayed opacity (after cascade)
const displayed = node.getDisplayedOpacity();
```

Visibility hides the node and all its children completely. Opacity allows semi-transparency.

Use color methods or the direct property:

```typescript
// Set color
node.setColor(cc.color(255, 0, 0));  // red
node.color = cc.color(0, 255, 0);     // green (direct)

// Read color
const col = node.getColor();          // cc.Color
const displayed = node.getDisplayedColor(); // after cascade

// Cascade color to children
node.setCascadeColorEnabled(true);
const cascading = node.isCascadeColorEnabled();
```

Color tints the node's visual. For sprites, `cc.color(255, 255, 255)` means no tint (original colors). `cc.color(255, 0, 0)` tints the sprite red.

Z-order controls which nodes render on top of others:

```typescript
// Local z-order (within parent)
node.setLocalZOrder(10);
node.setZOrder(10);       // alias
const z = node.getLocalZOrder();
node.zIndex = 10;         // direct property

// Global z-order (across entire scene)
node.setGlobalZOrder(100);
const gz = node.getGlobalZOrder();

// Reorder a child
parent.reorderChild(child, 5);

// Force sort
parent.sortAllChildren();
```

Higher z-order renders on top. Local z-order is relative to siblings. Global z-order overrides the scene graph hierarchy for rendering.

These methods return the node's bounding rectangle in different coordinate spaces:

```typescript
// Local space (relative to parent)
const localRect = node.getBoundingBox(); // cc.Rect

// World space
const worldRect = node.getBoundingBoxToWorld(); // cc.Rect

// Check collision between two nodes
const rectA = nodeA.getBoundingBoxToWorld();
const rectB = nodeB.getBoundingBoxToWorld();
if (cc.rectIntersectsRect(rectA, rectB)) {
    cc.log('Collision!');
}

// Check if a point is inside a node
const point = cc.p(200, 300);
if (cc.rectContainsPoint(node.getBoundingBoxToWorld(), point)) {
    cc.log('Point is inside node');
}
```

`getBoundingBox()` is in parent coordinates. `getBoundingBoxToWorld()` is in screen/world coordinates.

Convert between node-local and world coordinate spaces:

```typescript
// World → Node local
const localPt = node.convertToNodeSpace(cc.p(400, 300));

// Node local → World
const worldPt = node.convertToWorldSpace(cc.p(0, 0));

// Anchor-relative versions (origin at anchor point instead of bottom-left)
const localAR = node.convertToNodeSpaceAR(cc.p(400, 300));
const worldAR = node.convertToWorldSpaceAR(cc.p(0, 0));

// Convert touch to node space
const touchLocal = node.convertTouchToNodeSpace(touch);
const touchLocalAR = node.convertTouchToNodeSpaceAR(touch);

// Hit test example
const localPt2 = node.convertTouchToNodeSpace(touch);
const rect = cc.rect(0, 0, node.width, node.height);
if (cc.rectContainsPoint(rect, localPt2)) {
    cc.log('Touch hit the node');
}
```

Tags are numeric IDs, names are string IDs:

```typescript
// Set tag
node.setTag(100);
node.tag = 100; // direct property

// Set name
node.setName('player');

// Read
const tag = node.getTag();
const name = node.getName();

// Set/get user data (any type)
node.setUserData({ hp: 100, speed: 5 });
const data = node.getUserData();

// Find children by tag or name
const child = parent.getChildByTag(100);
const player = parent.getChildByName('player');

// Remove by tag/name
parent.removeChildByTag(100);
parent.removeChildByName('player');
```

Tags must be unique among siblings for reliable lookup. Names follow the same rule. Use `userData` for attaching arbitrary data to a node.

Control rotation (in degrees, clockwise) and scale:

```typescript
// Rotation
node.setRotation(45);          // 45 degrees clockwise
node.rotation = 45;            // direct property
const rot = node.getRotation();

// Per-axis rotation (skew-like)
node.setRotation(45, 60);     // rotationX=45, rotationY=60

// Scale
node.setScale(2.0);           // uniform 2x
node.setScale(2.0, 1.5);     // scaleX=2, scaleY=1.5
node.scale = 1.5;             // direct property
const s = node.getScale();
const sx = node.getScaleX();
const sy = node.getScaleY();

// Skew
node.setSkewX(15);
node.setSkewY(10);

// 3D rotation (JSB native only)
node.setRotation3D(new cc.math.Vec3(45, 30, 0));
```

Use `enumerateChildren` with a name pattern and callback:

```typescript
// Find all children named 'enemy'
parent.enumerateChildren('enemy', (node) => {
    cc.log('Found: ' + node.getName());
    return false; // continue searching (return true to stop)
});

// Find first match
let found: cc.Node | null = null;
parent.enumerateChildren('player', (node) => {
    found = node;
    return true; // stop after first match
});

// Use path pattern (recursive)
parent.enumerateChildren('//enemy', (node) => {
    // finds 'enemy' at any depth
    return false;
});
```

Return `true` from the callback to stop enumeration early, `false` to continue.

Use the window size to calculate the center position:

```typescript
const winSize = cc.director.getWinSize();
node.setPosition(winSize.width / 2, winSize.height / 2);

// Or using normalized position (0-1 relative to parent)
node.setNormalizedPosition(cc.p(0.5, 0.5));

// Make sure anchor is center for visual centering
node.setAnchorPoint(cc.p(0.5, 0.5));
```

If the node is a child of a non-fullscreen parent, use the parent's content size instead:
```typescript
const parentSize = parent.getContentSize();
node.setPosition(parentSize.width / 2, parentSize.height / 2);
```

Convert the touch to node-local coordinates and check against the bounding rect:

```typescript
function isNodeTouched(node: cc.Node, touch: cc.Touch): boolean {
    const localPt = node.convertTouchToNodeSpace(touch);
    const rect = cc.rect(0, 0, node.width, node.height);
    return cc.rectContainsPoint(rect, localPt);
}

// Usage in a touch listener:
cc.eventManager.addListener({
    event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
    onTouchBegan: (touch, event) => {
        if (isNodeTouched(mySprite, touch)) {
            cc.log('Sprite tapped!');
            return true;
        }
        return false;
    }
}, mySprite);
```

Use `cc.follow` to make the scene follow a target node:

```typescript
const player = new cc.Sprite('hero.png');
player.setPosition(100, 200);
this.addChild(player);

// Follow the player within a boundary
const mapRect = cc.rect(0, 0, 2000, 600);
this.runAction(cc.follow(player, mapRect));

// The layer/scene will scroll to keep 'player' centered,
// bounded by mapRect so the camera doesn't show outside the map.
```

The follow action is run on the parent node (layer/scene), not on the player. `mapRect` prevents the camera from going beyond the map edges.

Chain a callFunc or removeSelf action at the end of a sequence:

```typescript
// Method 1: cc.removeSelf()
const explosion = new cc.Sprite('explosion.png');
explosion.setPosition(200, 200);
this.addChild(explosion);
explosion.runAction(cc.sequence(
    cc.scaleTo(0.3, 2.0),
    cc.fadeOut(0.2),
    cc.removeSelf()
));

// Method 2: cc.callFunc with removeFromParent
const particle = new cc.Sprite('particle.png');
particle.setPosition(300, 300);
this.addChild(particle);
particle.runAction(cc.sequence(
    cc.moveBy(1.0, cc.p(0, 100)),
    cc.fadeOut(0.5),
    cc.callFunc(() => particle.removeFromParent(true))
));
```

Use the `schedule` method:

```typescript
class GameNode extends cc.Node {
    onEnter() {
        super.onEnter();

        // Every frame
        this.scheduleUpdate();

        // Every 2 seconds, forever
        this.schedule(this.spawnEnemy, 2.0);

        // Every 0.5s, 10 times, after 1s delay
        this.schedule(this.fireBullet, 0.5, 10, 1.0);

        // Once after 3 seconds
        this.scheduleOnce(this.showBoss, 3.0);
    }

    update(dt: number): void {
        // Called every frame
    }

    spawnEnemy(dt: number): void {
        // Called every 2 seconds
    }

    fireBullet(dt: number): void {
        // Called 10 times at 0.5s intervals
    }

    showBoss(dt: number): void {
        // Called once after 3 seconds
    }

    onExit() {
        this.unscheduleUpdate();
        this.unscheduleAllCallbacks();
        super.onExit();
    }
}
```

Use `pause()` and `resume()`:

```typescript
// Pause everything (actions + schedulers)
node.pause();

// Resume everything
node.resume();

// Or the older API:
node.pauseSchedulerAndActions();

// Pause specific: stop one action by tag
const action = cc.repeatForever(cc.rotateBy(1, 360));
action.setTag(42);
node.runAction(action);
node.stopActionByTag(42); // stops just that action

// Pause all and resume after delay
node.pause();
this.scheduleOnce(() => {
    node.resume();
}, 2.0);
```

`pause()` stops all scheduled callbacks and all running actions. `resume()` resumes them from where they paused.

Override the lifecycle methods and always call super:

```typescript
class GameSprite extends cc.Sprite {
    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        // Node was added to the stage
        this.scheduleUpdate();
        cc.log('GameSprite entered');
    }

    onExit(): void {
        // Node is being removed from the stage
        this.unscheduleAllCallbacks();
        cc.log('GameSprite exited');
        super.onExit();
    }

    onEnterTransitionDidFinish(): void {
        super.onEnterTransitionDidFinish();
        // Scene transition completed
        this.startGameplay();
    }

    onExitTransitionDidStart(): void {
        // Scene exit transition starting
        this.saveProgress();
        super.onExitTransitionDidStart();
    }

    cleanup(): void {
        // Stops all actions and scheduled callbacks
        super.cleanup();
    }

    update(dt: number): void {
        // Per-frame update
    }
}
```

Order: `onEnter` -> `onEnterTransitionDidFinish` -> (running) -> `onExitTransitionDidStart` -> `onExit` -> `cleanup`.

Layer sprites at different z-orders and move them at different rates:

```typescript
class ParallaxScene extends cc.Scene {
    private backgrounds: { node: cc.Sprite; speed: number }[] = [];

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();

        const layers = [
            { img: 'bg_sky.png', z: -3, speed: 0.1 },
            { img: 'bg_mountains.png', z: -2, speed: 0.3 },
            { img: 'bg_trees.png', z: -1, speed: 0.6 },
            { img: 'bg_ground.png', z: 0, speed: 1.0 },
        ];

        layers.forEach(cfg => {
            const sprite = new cc.Sprite(cfg.img);
            sprite.setAnchorPoint(cc.p(0, 0));
            sprite.setPosition(0, 0);
            this.addChild(sprite, cfg.z);
            this.backgrounds.push({ node: sprite, speed: cfg.speed });
        });

        this.scheduleUpdate();
    }

    update(dt: number): void {
        const scrollSpeed = 100; // pixels per second
        this.backgrounds.forEach(bg => {
            bg.node.x -= scrollSpeed * bg.speed * dt;
            // Wrap around
            if (bg.node.x <= -bg.node.width) {
                bg.node.x += bg.node.width;
            }
        });
    }
}
```

Build a composite character using child nodes:

```typescript
function createCharacter(): cc.Node {
    const root = new cc.Node();
    root.setContentSize(cc.size(64, 128));
    root.setAnchorPoint(cc.p(0.5, 0));

    const body = new cc.Sprite('char_body.png');
    body.setPosition(32, 50);
    body.setName('body');
    root.addChild(body, 0);

    const head = new cc.Sprite('char_head.png');
    head.setPosition(0, 40); // relative to body
    head.setName('head');
    body.addChild(head, 1);

    const leftArm = new cc.Sprite('char_arm.png');
    leftArm.setPosition(-25, 10);
    leftArm.setAnchorPoint(cc.p(1, 0.5)); // pivot at shoulder
    leftArm.setName('leftArm');
    body.addChild(leftArm, -1);

    const rightArm = new cc.Sprite('char_arm.png');
    rightArm.setPosition(25, 10);
    rightArm.flippedX = true;
    rightArm.setAnchorPoint(cc.p(0, 0.5));
    rightArm.setName('rightArm');
    body.addChild(rightArm, -1);

    return root;
}

const hero = createCharacter();
hero.setPosition(200, 50);
this.addChild(hero);

// Animate arm swing
const arm = hero.getChildByName('body').getChildByName('leftArm');
arm.runAction(cc.repeatForever(cc.sequence(
    cc.rotateTo(0.3, 30),
    cc.rotateTo(0.3, -30)
)));
```

Iterate through nodes and test each one:

```typescript
const interactiveNodes: cc.Node[] = [node1, node2, node3];

cc.eventManager.addListener({
    event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
    onTouchBegan: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event): boolean => {
        for (const node of interactiveNodes) {
            if (!node.isVisible()) continue;
            const localPt = node.convertTouchToNodeSpace(touch);
            const rect = cc.rect(0, 0, node.width, node.height);
            if (cc.rectContainsPoint(rect, localPt)) {
                cc.log('Tapped: ' + node.getName());
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
}, this);
```

For many nodes, use `getBoundingBoxToWorld()` for a faster pre-check before converting coordinates:
```typescript
const worldRect = node.getBoundingBoxToWorld();
const touchLoc = touch.getLocation();
if (cc.rectContainsPoint(worldRect, touchLoc)) { /* hit */ }
```

Access and set the shader program on a node:

```typescript
// Get current shader
const shader = node.getShaderProgram();
const state = node.getGLProgramState();

// Set a built-in shader
const grayShader = cc.shaderCache.getProgram('ShaderPositionTextureColor');
node.setShaderProgram(grayShader);

// Use GL program state for uniforms
const newState = cc.GLProgramState.getOrCreateWithGLProgram(grayShader);
newState.setUniformFloat('u_time', 1.0);
node.setGLProgramState(newState);
```

Note: Custom shaders work in JSB (native) but have limited support in HTML5. Always test on both platforms.

Attach a physics body to a node:

```typescript
const sprite = new cc.Sprite('ball.png');
sprite.setPosition(240, 400);

const body = new cc.PhysicsBody.createCircle(sprite.width / 2, cc.PhysicsMaterial(1, 0.5, 0.3));
body.setDynamic(true);
sprite.setPhysicsBody(body);
this.addChild(sprite);

// Read physics body later
const existingBody = sprite.getPhysicsBody();
if (existingBody) {
    existingBody.setVelocity(cc.p(100, 200));
}
```

The scene must have physics enabled for bodies to work. Call `this.getScene()` to access the scene from any node.

Apply random offsets to a container node:

```typescript
function shakeNode(node: cc.Node, duration: number, intensity: number): void {
    const originalPos = node.getPosition();
    const shakes = Math.floor(duration / 0.05);
    const actions: cc.FiniteTimeAction[] = [];

    for (let i = 0; i < shakes; i++) {
        const dx = (Math.random() - 0.5) * 2 * intensity;
        const dy = (Math.random() - 0.5) * 2 * intensity;
        actions.push(cc.moveTo(0.05, cc.p(originalPos.x + dx, originalPos.y + dy)));
    }
    actions.push(cc.moveTo(0.05, originalPos)); // return to origin

    node.runAction(cc.sequence(actions));
}

// Usage: shake the game layer
shakeNode(this.gameLayer, 0.5, 10);
```

